        "author": {
          "name": "John L. Hammond",
          "email": "john.hammond@intel.com",
          "date": "2013-07-27 14:55:09.000000000",
          "tz": -300
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "John L. Hammond",
          "email": "john.hammond@intel.com",
          "date": "2013-07-27 14:55:09.000000000",
          "tz": -300
        },
        "subject": "LU-3601 ldlm: examine all waiting ibits locks on reprocess",
        "message": "LU-3601 ldlm: examine all waiting ibits locks on reprocess\n\nIn the reprocessing case of ldlm_process_inodebits_lock(), return\nLDLM_ITER_CONTINUE even if the current lock could not be granted. This\nwill cause ldlm_reprocess_queue() to grant all locks that do not\nconflict with a granted lock and do not conflict with a preceeding\n(blocked) lock on the waiting list. This does not reorder conflicting\nlocks but does reorder the waiting list and makes the handling of\nreprocess more similar to that of enqueue. The benefit this approach\nis better liveness after lock cancellation (which may be required to\nsupport HSM) at the expense making the worst case complexity of\nreprocessing quadratic in the size of the waiting list.\n\nSigned-off-by: John L. Hammond <john.hammond@intel.com>\nChange-Id: Ia854353fdbf63b2a52da1e95ce0f3c1ebe2f2682\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
